 | [[FOXP2]] || || 7q31 || The FOXP2 gene is of interest because it is known to be associated with developmental language and speech deficits.<ref>{{vcite journal |author=Marui T, Koishi S, Funatogawa I, ''et al.'' |author.= |title=No association of FOXP2 and PTPRZ1 on 7q31 with autism from the Japanese population |journal=Neurosci Res |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=91–4 |year=2005 |pmid=15998549 |doi=10.1016/j.neures.2005.05.003}}</ref><ref>{{vcite journal |author=Gauthier J, Joober R, Mottron L, ''et al.'' |author.= |title=Mutation screening of FOXP2 in individuals diagnosed with autistic disorder |journal=Am J Med Genet A |volume=118 |issue=2 |pages=172–5 |year=2003 |pmid=12655497 |doi=10.1002/ajmg.a.10105}}</ref> A 2008 study found that FOXP2 binds to and down-regulates CNTNAP2, and that the FOXP2-CNTNAP2 pathway links distinct syndromes involving disrupted language.<ref>{{vcite journal |author= Vernes SC, Newbury DF, Abrahams BS ''et al.'' |author.= |title= A functional genetic link between distinct developmental language disorders |journal= N Engl J Med |volume=359 |issue=22 |pages=2337–45 |year=2008 |pmid=18987363 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0802828 |laysummary=http://sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/38326/title/A_genetic_pathway_to_language_disorders |laysource= Science News |laydate=2008-11-05 |pmc=2756409}}</ref>

